    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hue name for one of the three primary additive colors; that portion of the spectrum lying at the lowest frequencies of light discernible by the human eye, with a wavelength range between 630 and 760 nanometers. The term may refer to any of this group of colors that vary in lightness and saturation. Examples of red color in nature are that of blood and ripe cherries.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000048174/American Heritage Dictionary (1982)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Eén van de drie primaire additieve kleuren; dat deel van het spectrum dat zich bevindt in het laagste nog door het menselijk oog waarneembare lichtfrequentiebereik, met een golflengte tussen 630 en 760 nanometer. De term kan verwijzen naar alle in helderheid en verzadiging variërende kleurschakeringen binnen deze groep kleuren. Voorbeelden van de kleur rood in de natuur zijn de kleur van bloed en rijpe kersen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指色相名稱，為加色法三原色之一。在光譜上，紅色是人類肉眼可識別的光線中頻率最低者，波長則在630奈米到760奈米之間。在紅色系中帶著不同明度與飽和度的色彩，皆可稱為「紅色」。舉例來說，在大自然中鮮血的顏色與成熟櫻桃的顏色就是紅色。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Nome de matiz para uma das três cores aditivas primárias; aquela porção do espectro que fica nas frequências mais baixas de luz discerníveis pelo olho humano, com uma faixa de comprimento de onda entre 630 e 760 nanômetros. O termo pode se referir a qualquer um desse grupo de cores que variam em luminosidade e saturação. Exemplos de cor vermelha na natureza são o sangue e as cerejas maduras.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
